Files:
- platform/mcp-server/src/dev-proxy.ts

Context (three separate bugs):

(a) splice(-1,1) bug — in `whenReady` (lines 265–292), the timeout handler:
```typescript
pending.splice(pending.indexOf(entry), 1);
```
If `entry` was already removed by `drainPending` (line 85: `for (const fn of pending.splice(0)) fn()`), `indexOf(entry)` returns -1. `splice(-1, 1)` removes the last element — dropping a legitimate pending request.

Fix: `const idx = pending.indexOf(entry); if (idx >= 0) pending.splice(idx, 1);`

(b) Worker crash — the `child.on('exit')` handler around line 252–257:
```typescript
child.on('exit', code => {
  worker = null;
  workerPort = null;
  // ...
});
```
There is no restart logic. After a crash, all subsequent requests stay in `pending` indefinitely.

Fix: Track whether the exit was planned (from `startWorker()`'s `worker.kill('SIGTERM')`) vs unexpected. If unexpected (not killed by us), call `startWorker()` with a small delay:
```typescript
child.on('exit', (code, signal) => {
  if (worker === child) { // only restart if this is still the current worker
    worker = null;
    workerPort = null;
    if (!plannedKill) {
      setTimeout(() => startWorker(), 1000);
    }
  }
});
```
Use a `let plannedKill = false` flag set to `true` before `worker.kill('SIGTERM')` in `startWorker()`, cleared on process message/exit.

(c) pendingWsProtocol race — look for `pendingWsProtocol` in the file and understand its role. If it's a module-level variable set in one callback and read in another, the same pattern as `_pendingConnectionId` in http-routes.ts (see PRD mcp-server-security). Fix similarly by storing per-upgrade state in the WebSocket data or a Map keyed by the socket object.

Constraints:
- Read the full `startWorker()` function before implementing the restart logic
- Do NOT restart the worker more than once every 1000ms to avoid restart storms
- When the worker restarts, existing `reinitializeSessions` logic should handle re-connecting sessions

Files:
- platform/mcp-server/src/file-watcher.ts

Context:
(a) null filename — `fs.watch` on Linux may pass `null` as the `filename` argument for some inotify events (e.g., attribute changes). The current code pattern in `watchPlugin` and `watchPendingPlugin` is:
```typescript
(eventType, filename) => {
  if (filename === TOOLS_FILENAME) { ... }
  else if (filename === ADAPTER_FILENAME) { ... }
}
```
When `filename === null`, both conditions are false and the event is silently ignored. This means a file change that produced a null filename will not trigger hot reload.

Fix: when `filename === null`, re-read both `TOOLS_FILENAME` and `ADAPTER_FILENAME` to handle the event conservatively:
```typescript
(eventType, filename) => {
  if (filename === null) {
    // On Linux, filename can be null for some events. Re-check both files.
    handleToolsJsonChange(pluginName, dir);
    handleIifeChange(pluginName, dir);
    return;
  }
  if (filename === TOOLS_FILENAME) { handleToolsJsonChange(pluginName, dir); }
  else if (filename === ADAPTER_FILENAME) { handleIifeChange(pluginName, dir); }
}
```
Read the actual handler names in the file before writing — they may be `onToolsChanged` or similar.

(b) EMFILE escalation — in `startConfigWatching`, when `watch()` fails with EMFILE:
```typescript
} catch (err) {
  if ((err as NodeJS.ErrnoException).code === 'EMFILE') {
    if (fw.mtimePollTimerId !== null) {
      // escalate polling
    }
  }
}
```
If `fw.mtimePollTimerId` is null (because `startMtimePolling` hasn't run yet), the escalation is skipped.

Fix: remove the `if (fw.mtimePollTimerId !== null)` guard and always call `startMtimePolling` (or equivalent). If polling is already running, `startMtimePolling` should be idempotent (check its implementation).

Constraints:
- The null-filename fallback (re-checking both files) may result in double invocation on some events — ensure `handleToolsJsonChange` and `handleIifeChange` are idempotent (they should already be, since they compare mtimes)
- Do NOT change the mtime comparison logic — only add the null guard
